Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,
Happy Friday and welcome back to our 27th Weekly Dose of Optimism. Pretty c=
ontent-heavy week here at Not Boring. If you enjoyed reading or listening t=
o any of it, we=E2=80=99d appreciate if you could share it with a friend or=
 colleague.
Let=E2=80=99s get to it=E2=80=A6and Go Birds =F0=9F=A6=85
The Weekly Dose is brought to you by=E2=80=A6 WUDU [ https://substack.com/r=
edirect/21c05db9-208b-4cd2-a2ca-fc03bdc61266?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7=
GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
I have many weaknesses, but the most glaring is that I=E2=80=99m a terrible=
 gift giver. I can=E2=80=99t remember a holiday or special occasion when I =
wasn=E2=80=99t scramble-shopping for Puja=E2=80=99s present with under 48 h=
ours left on the clock.=20
If that sounds familiar, I got you covered for Valentine=E2=80=99s Day. Or =
rather, Puja, my mom, and my sister do. Last year, they teamed up to launch=
 a new handbag company, WUDU [ https://substack.com/redirect/21c05db9-208b-=
4cd2-a2ca-fc03bdc61266?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqO=
sa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].=20
WUDU bags are designed in the USA and handcrafted in=C2=A0Ghana using indig=
enous danta wood=C2=A0and genuine leather offcuts sourced primarily from It=
aly. Each bag is handcrafted and one-of-a-kind, so you=E2=80=99ll look extr=
a thoughtful.
The bags have a great backstory (handcrafted by a female entrepreneur/manuf=
acturer that my sister knows in Ghana), but most importantly they are high =
quality=E2=80=A6and have sold out every trunk show they=E2=80=99ve been a p=
art of.
With Valentine=E2=80=99s Day right around the corner, a WUDU [ https://subs=
tack.com/redirect/21c05db9-208b-4cd2-a2ca-fc03bdc61266?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Qi=
fQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] bag makes for the perfect =
gift for the special women in your life. They=E2=80=99re currently producin=
g in small batches, so order now before they sell out (or before you forget=
 until the last minute again):
(1) Atomic AI: Unlocking RNA [ https://substack.com/redirect/9fe30a13-1589-=
44f4-a254-d292b18e9282?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqO=
sa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Packy McCormick [ https://substack.com/redirect/96e6d55c-4fc3-4565-9840-389=
671dfeb5d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNp=
U ] and Elliot Hershberg [ https://substack.com/redirect/ae56dd6f-c8fc-46a6=
-840c-7892c3a5ee8e?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-=
6m8ExkRNpU ] for Not Boring
Atomic AI is a perfect example of the kind of company we want to invest in =
at Not Boring Capital. It=E2=80=99s built on cutting edge science at the in=
tersection of Bits and Atoms, has a path to becoming a $10B+ company, and a=
s importantly, will bend the world=E2=80=99s trajectory upwards if it succe=
eds. Specifically, by unlocking the structure of RNA, Atomic AI could unloc=
k the potential of RNA-targeting and RNA-based medicines, help cure previou=
sly incurable diseases, and save millions of lives.
Packy and Elliot Hershberg [ https://substack.com/redirect/ae56dd6f-c8fc-46=
a6-840c-7892c3a5ee8e?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa=
8-6m8ExkRNpU ] (Not Boring Capital Biotech Partner) published a deep dive o=
n one of the most fascinating, and we think important, companies in the Not=
 Boring Capital portfolio. Atomic AI is developing the cutting-edge fusion =
of machine learning and structural biology to unlock RNA drug discovery. Th=
e easiest way to think about the company is like AlphaFold for RNA.=20
If Atomic AI is successful, it could unlock the potential of RNA-targeting =
and RNA-based medicines, help cure previously incurable diseases, and save =
millions of lives.=20
(2) How to Be 18 Years Old Again for Only $2 Million a Year [ https://subst=
ack.com/redirect/fed69f1e-0fbd-44d1-a64c-359cbc9ed87f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Qif=
Q.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Ashlee Vance [ https://substack.com/redirect/d3988a5b-0b74-4da8-a8bf-cdb9e5=
552a30?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]=
 for Bloomberg Businessweek
Johnson, 45, is an ultrawealthy software entrepreneur who has more than 30 =
doctors and health experts monitoring his every bodily function=E2=80=A6The=
 team, led by 29-year-old regenerative medicine physician Oliver Zolman [ h=
ttps://substack.com/redirect/bf515ed6-a534-4cbf-94e9-8385c9656856?j=3DeyJ1I=
joiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], has committed =
to help reverse the aging process [ https://substack.com/redirect/539e0d0a-=
b911-4110-a74f-2c94040facd3?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXe=
pKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] in every one of Johnson=E2=80=99s organs=E2=80=A6.Thi=
s year, he=E2=80=99s on track to spend at least $2 million on his body. He =
wants to have the brain, heart, lungs, liver, kidneys, tendons, teeth, skin=
, hair, bladder, penis and rectum of an 18-year-old.
It=E2=80=99s been reported that LeBron James spends $1.5 million on his hea=
lth & fitness each year. Bryan Johnson, the founder of payments platform Br=
aintree, spends 30% more than that =E2=80=94 $2 million dollars per year. (=
We just use Fount [ https://substack.com/redirect/61dc087f-2bae-4c68-a1aa-8=
9d85084bccd?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkR=
NpU ] here at Not Boring.) Johnson has taken the idea of the quantified-sel=
f to the extreme and is on a quest to reverse aging. Supposedly it=E2=80=99=
s working: the 45 year old has a =E2=80=9Cbiological age=E2=80=9D of 30, ac=
cording to some doctors.=20
One way to view this story is that a wacky ~billionaire is on some quixotic=
 quest to live forever, because how could the world live without him?! The =
clich=C3=A9 of the biohacking, ultra-optimized techbro that is trying to co=
mpensate for some deep-seated insecurity exists for a reason.
But a more charitable view here=E2=80=94and the view that I happen to hold=
=E2=80=94is that Johnson is taking on an extreme burden, which may ultimate=
ly produce some generalizable health & wellness learnings. While I don=E2=
=80=99t think it=E2=80=99s really feasible for the average person to exactl=
y follow =E2=80=9CThe Blueprint [ https://substack.com/redirect/b6dceb0b-c3=
de-47dc-b2f1-fa3f94b418c3?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepK=
bqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ],=E2=80=9D I do think his principles are pretty reasonab=
le and there are some easily adoptable tips and heuristics. At a high-level=
, if Johnson and his team are able to prove out a legitimate plan for age-r=
eversal and scale that beyond just Johnson himself, than that would obvious=
ly be pretty paradigm shifting.=20
(3) America Isn=E2=80=99t Ready for the Weight-Loss-Drug Revolution That=E2=
=80=99s Coming [ https://substack.com/redirect/e8b44577-26e3-4ea3-ad78-1fb3=
c87ea190?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU=
 ]
Derek Thompson [ https://substack.com/redirect/9c0541e8-5fa1-4323-bfb0-fd45=
f53173f0?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU=
 ] for Plain English
We=E2=80=99ve written a lot about the promise of GLP-1 weight loss medicati=
ons. The early read from studies and reputable experts is that they can hel=
p people lose up to 20% of their weight, with few serious adverse side effe=
cts. These medications are, for many people that have struggled with obesit=
y, miracle drugs.
Derek Thompson had Dr. Susan Yanovski [ https://substack.com/redirect/7c6e7=
746-9b6a-48d5-a930-2d708d4f03ab?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjm=
lXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], the co-Director of the Office of Obesity Researc=
h at the NIH, on his podcast to discuss the history of weight-loss treatmen=
t in America, how GLP-1s are changing everything, and what that might mean =
for a society that places so much emphasis on weight. The big takeaway from=
 Dr. Yanovski is that, for many people, weight management is less a matter =
of willpower or personal responsibility, but more so a medical condition th=
at needs to be treated as such.=20
As a note, we know we=E2=80=99ve been covering this topic repeatedly in The=
 Weekly Dose of Optimism. It is our view that this is one of the more impor=
tant stories in health, tech, and society right now. We also recognize that=
 there=E2=80=99s a bit of darker side to this story =E2=80=94 medication ab=
use, anecdotal adverse side effects, and just America=E2=80=99s (let=E2=80=
=99s be real here, mostly superficial) obsession with weight. We=E2=80=99ll=
 try our best to monitor and meter our excitement as the rollout of these d=
rugs occurs over the coming years.=20
(4) Aviation Startup ZeroAvia Flies Largest-Ever Hydrogen Electric Aircraft=
 [ https://substack.com/redirect/dfe9abf8-ab81-47bb-963c-24f062ec980f?j=3De=
yJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Andy Corbley [ https://substack.com/redirect/3a6aebc3-c071-46f2-82f0-02ef18=
48ca6f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]=
 for Good New Network,  h/t Nick Van Osdol [ https://substack.com/redirect/=
0bfb53f6-cbe0-4df7-b3cb-46654e8b7984?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNu=
aMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
This is a major moment, not just for ZeroAvia, but for the aviation industr=
y as a whole, as it shows that true zero-emission commercial flight is only=
 a few years away. The first flight of our 19-seat aircraft shows just how =
scalable our technology is and highlights the rapid progress of zero-emissi=
on propulsion.
This aviation startup, ZeroAvia, made history this week by flying the large=
st-ever hydrogen-electric fueled aircraft. While you won=E2=80=99t find Ame=
rican Airlines or Delta replacing their fleet of jet-fuel guzzling birds an=
ytime soon, ZeroAvia=E2=80=99s succesful test-flight is a hopeful sign that=
 we are closer to commercial zero-emissions flights.
Aviation accounts for ~2.5% of global global CO2 pollution (which is relati=
vely sizeable) but such a small percentage of people are responsible for th=
at impact. It=E2=80=99s estimated that only 5% of the global population has=
 ever even been on a flight =E2=80=94 and within that flying sub-population=
, some folks are definitely have an outsized effect (private flights, frequ=
ent flyers, etc).
If we can replace all of those fuel guzzling jets with hydrogen-powered air=
craft, it won=E2=80=99t solve climate change, but it=E2=80=99ll definitely =
make a nice positive dent.=20
(5) Joe Biden's conditional optimism about America [ https://substack.com/r=
edirect/98f1ee68-018d-42c4-a2ea-8574a2ebf904?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7=
GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Matthew Yglesias [ https://substack.com/redirect/6737c7fb-ca05-408f-b97a-8a=
b62e2d0835?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRN=
pU ] for Slow Boring
Biden calls himself a =E2=80=9Ccongenital optimist,=E2=80=9D but his life h=
as famously been marked by tragedy and he=E2=80=99s no Pollyanna. He believ=
es the country has genuine concrete advantages =E2=80=94 a favorable geogra=
phical location; abundant natural resources; a large, skilled, and highly-m=
otivated population =E2=80=94 and that with those advantages we can surmoun=
t problems and lead the world, if we are united.
And that=E2=80=99s where Joe Biden comes in.
We generally steer clear of politics here at Not Boring. But, to be transpa=
rent, we=E2=80=99re rooting for Joe Biden. He holds an optimistic view of A=
merica that we tend to agree with. To be clear, we=E2=80=99re not =E2=80=9C=
you must support the President because he=E2=80=99s the President=E2=80=9D =
maximalists. Trump=E2=80=99s vision for America (and his general approach i=
n bringing that vision to life) was not one we supported. But Biden=E2=80=
=99s vision? Yes, that=E2=80=99s something that we can get behind. It=E2=80=
=99s something like: we=E2=80=99re not perfect, but if we work together we =
can definitely be the best.
Do we agree with all of his policies? No.=20
Do we love the fact that an 80 year old is President? No.
Is his approach of realpolitiking a bit icky at times? Sure.
Is the whole Hunter situation sad and absurd? Definitely.
Is the hypocrisy of the whole classified docs thing a bit face-palmy? Yes. =
=20
Will there be better (even Republican) Presidential candidates during the n=
ext election? Possibly.
But that=E2=80=99s doesn=E2=80=99t mean we=E2=80=99re not rooting for Joe. =
And despite his shortcomings, he=E2=80=99s actually getting a lot of stuff =
done (China hasn=E2=80=99t looked weaker in a few decades!) and delivering =
on his promise of progress through compromise.
This Ygelsias profile does a nice job of framing how Biden is operating tod=
ay and why, despite all of the reasons we listed above, it might actually b=
e working.=20
Bonus: Not Boring Founders: Andy Chatham, Dimo [ https://substack.com/redir=
ect/c0dc353d-9229-4be7-a07b-04078170d6c9?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_=
ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Packy had on Andy Chatham, the co-founder and CEO of DIMO. DIMO is a connec=
ted vehicle platform built on Web3 rails. Our view at Not Boring is that th=
e next wave of crypto applications that take off will connect crypto to the=
 real world and to apps that have value on their own. DIMO is a perfect exa=
mple of this.
Speaking of Not Boring Founders, NBC portfolio company Melonfrost announced=
 its $7M seed round [ https://substack.com/redirect/59778131-07d0-4cb8-b7d4=
-66a2421a5431?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8Ex=
kRNpU ]. Its one of the most ambitious projects in our portfolio. Melonfros=
t is building the world=E2=80=99s first evolutionary prediction engine. Fin=
d out exactly what that means in the next episode of Not Boring founders.
